# Portfolio Studio Site

## Operating Principle

Make the work, person, or studio legible before making the site clever. Treat the website as a decision surface: visitors should quickly understand who this is, what kind of work they do, why it is credible, and what to do next.

## First Pass

Start by identifying four things from the user's materials or by asking only if missing:

1. Primary goal: showcase, inquiries, hiring, sales, press, archive, audience building, or experimental expression.
2. Audience: clients, recruiters, collaborators, collectors, fans, students, curators, or peers.
3. Core material: projects, images, videos, writing, services, credentials, testimonials, process, or productized offers.
4. Desired tone: quiet gallery, editorial, technical, luxury, playful, experimental, commercial, academic, or utilitarian.

If the user has not supplied enough content, create a useful placeholder content model and label assumptions clearly. Do not wait for perfect inputs when a reasonable first version can be built.

## Site Type Decision

Choose the dominant type, then adapt the structure:

- Portfolio: emphasize selected work, visual browsing, concise project details, and contact.
- Personal brand: emphasize identity, expertise, point of view, proof, writing, and links.
- Studio site: emphasize services, case studies, clients, process, team, and inquiries.
- Case-study portfolio: emphasize problem, role, process, solution, outcomes, and reflection.
- Archive/gallery: emphasize media quality, taxonomy, pacing, filtering, and image performance.
- Service landing site: emphasize offer clarity, proof, packages or process, objection handling, and conversion.
- Experimental site-as-work: make interaction part of the work, but preserve orientation, accessibility, and contact.

For deeper examples and IA patterns, read `references/patterns.md`.

## Product Workflow

1. Define the visitor journey.
   - Landing: answer "what is this and why should I care?"
   - Browsing: let visitors compare work without friction.
   - Deepening: provide project context, role, process, and outcomes.
   - Trust: add credentials, clients, testimonials, press, awards, metrics, or recognizable collaborators.
   - Action: make email, booking, resume, purchase, or social follow obvious.

2. Select content ruthlessly.
   - Prefer 6-12 strong projects over a large uneven archive.
   - Put the most representative work first, not necessarily the newest.
   - Use project summaries that state medium, role, year, and result.
   - Avoid generic claims unless paired with proof.

3. Model the content.
   - Define project fields before building UI: title, slug, year, discipline, role, client, cover image, gallery, summary, challenge, approach, outcome, links, credits, tags.
   - Keep projects in Markdown, MDX, JSON, CMS, or database records when the site will be updated.
   - Hard-code only tiny sites where future editing is unlikely.

4. Design conversion paths.
   - Use persistent or repeated contact entry points on commercial sites.
   - Include a specific call to action near proof-heavy sections.
   - For hiring, include resume/CV, role clarity, and project responsibilities.
   - For studios, include service scope and engagement model before contact.

## Design Workflow

1. Establish the first-viewport signal.
   - The hero must reveal the person/studio/product/work immediately.
   - Avoid template-like generic headlines. Use a literal name, practice, offer, or creative domain.
   - Show actual work or meaningful media early; do not hide all evidence below the fold.

2. Let the work lead.
   - Use restraint in decoration, gradients, cards, and copy.
   - Match layout density to the practice: galleries can breathe; business services need scannable proof; technical portfolios need context and links.
   - Make image crops intentional and stable across breakpoints.

3. Create visual identity through specific choices.
   - Choose typography, spacing, motion, color, and image treatment to match the user's domain.
   - Avoid one-note palettes and overused generic dark/purple/cream looks unless the brand demands them.
   - Use icons for compact controls and familiar actions where appropriate.

4. Design responsive behavior first-class.
   - Check mobile navigation, image aspect ratios, long titles, CTA placement, and gallery controls.
   - Use fixed aspect ratios or responsive constraints for grids, covers, tiles, and carousels to prevent layout shift.
   - Ensure text never overlaps or overflows buttons, cards, or media.

5. Use motion carefully.
   - Motion should help pacing, transition, or reveal hierarchy.
   - Avoid scroll effects that make browsing work slower or inaccessible.
   - Respect reduced-motion preferences.

## Technical Workflow

Prefer the simplest architecture that preserves image quality, speed, and maintainability.

- Static-first frameworks: Astro, Next.js, Nuxt, SvelteKit, Eleventy, or plain HTML for very small sites.
- Content: Markdown/MDX/JSON/CMS collections for projects; avoid scattering project data through components.
- Images: responsive sizes, explicit dimensions, lazy loading below the fold, modern formats, and careful compression.
- Media: poster frames for video, deferred embeds, captions/credits where relevant.
- SEO: unique title/description, Open Graph image, semantic HTML, sitemap, robots, canonical URLs, alt text.
- Accessibility: keyboard navigation, focus states, color contrast, alt text, labels, reduced motion, semantic landmarks.
- Performance: optimized fonts, no unnecessary animation libraries, avoid huge first-screen media, test Lighthouse/Core Web Vitals.
- Deployment: Vercel, Netlify, Cloudflare Pages, GitHub Pages, or static hosting as appropriate.
- Forms: use a reliable form provider, email API, booking link, or mailto only for very simple sites.
- Analytics: add privacy-friendly analytics when the site has business goals.

When building with an existing repo, follow the existing framework, component system, CSS conventions, and content source. Do not introduce a new stack just because it is fashionable.

## Implementation Checklist

Use this checklist before final delivery:

- Clear site type and primary goal.
- Homepage communicates identity/work/offer in the first viewport.
- Project list is browsable and selected work is prioritized.
- Project detail pages include enough context to prove contribution and quality.
- Contact or next action is obvious.
- Mobile layout is deliberately designed, not merely squeezed.
- Images have stable dimensions, responsive variants, and sensible alt text.
- Navigation works with keyboard and small screens.
- SEO metadata and social preview are present.
- Performance is checked, especially image weight and font loading.
- Visual QA is performed in browser screenshots for desktop and mobile after frontend changes.

## Output Expectations

When asked to design, return a concrete site concept: type, audience, IA, homepage sections, project detail structure, visual direction, content model, and implementation approach.

When asked to build, implement the site, run the local app if needed, verify it in browser/screenshots, and report the URL plus key files changed.

When asked to review, lead with issues that harm clarity, credibility, conversion, accessibility, performance, or maintainability, with file/line references when available.
